<h1>Authorization</h1>

<p>
    Nxt doesn't bundle an auth provider — wire whichever fits (cookies, Identity, OIDC, JWT)
    in your <code>Program.cs</code> via <code>NxtHostOptions</code>. The framework just
    needs you to:
</p>

<ol>
    <li>Register services (<code>AddAuthentication</code>, <code>AddAuthorization</code>, …)
        in <code>ConfigureServices</code>.</li>
    <li>Insert <code>UseAuthentication</code> + <code>UseAuthorization</code> in
        <code>ConfigureMiddleware</code>.</li>
</ol>

<h2>ASP.NET Core Identity with cookies + SQLite</h2>
<pre><code>await NxtHost.RunAsync(args, opts =&gt;
&#123;
    opts.ConfigureServices = builder =&gt;
    &#123;
        builder.Services.AddDbContext&lt;AppDbContext&gt;(o =&gt;
            o.UseSqlite("Data Source=app.db"));

        builder.Services
            .AddIdentity&lt;IdentityUser, IdentityRole&gt;(o =&gt; o.Password.RequiredLength = 6)
            .AddEntityFrameworkStores&lt;AppDbContext&gt;()
            .AddDefaultTokenProviders();

        builder.Services.ConfigureApplicationCookie(o =&gt;
        &#123;
            o.LoginPath = "/auth/login";
            o.LogoutPath = "/auth/logout";
        &#125;);

        builder.Services.AddAuthorization();
        builder.Services.AddCascadingAuthenticationState();
    &#125;;

    opts.ConfigureMiddleware = app =&gt;
    &#123;
        app.UseAuthentication();
        app.UseAuthorization();
    &#125;;
&#125;);</code></pre>

<h2>Protecting routes</h2>
<p>Two options.</p>

<h3>Per page</h3>
<pre><code>@@attribute [Authorize]
&lt;h1&gt;Profile&lt;/h1&gt;</code></pre>

<h3>Per subtree (cascading)</h3>
<p>
    Drop <code>@@attribute [Authorize]</code> on a layout — Nxt's generator copies it onto
    every page beneath the layout. Add roles or policies the same way:
</p>
<pre><code>@@* Pages/Admin/_layout.razor *@@
@@attribute [Authorize(Roles="admin")]

&lt;aside&gt;...&lt;/aside&gt;
@@Body</code></pre>

<p>
    Unauthenticated requests are bounced to whatever you set as
    <code>options.LoginPath</code>, with <code>?ReturnUrl=…</code> appended.
</p>

<h2>Sign-in / sign-out endpoints</h2>
<p>
    A typical pattern: a Razor form posts to a colocated API endpoint that calls
    <code>SignInManager</code>. The endpoint files live under
    <code>Pages/Auth/api/</code> so they're URL-routed to <code>/api/auth/*</code> and sit
    right next to the forms.
</p>
<pre><code>public class Login(SignInManager&lt;IdentityUser&gt; signIn)
&#123;
    public async Task&lt;IResult&gt; POST(HttpContext ctx)
    &#123;
        var form = await ctx.Request.ReadFormAsync();
        var result = await signIn.PasswordSignInAsync(
            form["email"]!, form["password"]!,
            isPersistent: true, lockoutOnFailure: false);
        return result.Succeeded
            ? Results.Redirect("/dashboard")
            : Results.Redirect("/auth/login?error=invalid");
    &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>
